:::summary
The Holy Ghost — also called the Holy Spirit — is the third person of the Trinity in orthodox Christian theology and a distinct member of the Godhead in Latter-day Saint theology. Present at Creation, poured out at Pentecost, and dwelling in the hearts of believers, the Holy Ghost is the divine Comforter promised by Jesus Christ himself, the agent of conversion and sanctification, the source of spiritual gifts, and the witness of truth. To know the Holy Ghost is to understand how God is present and active in human life.
:::

